  "id": "",
  "summary": "Clipboard logger disguised as Bittensor burn monitor exfiltrates copied data to hardcoded Telegram bot",
  "details": "Package is advertised on PyPI as a 'Bittensor subnet burn rate monitoring' tool, but the Cython-compiled core module (bittensor_burn_watch/core.so) is a clipboard surveillance agent. It reads the user's clipboard via Win32 API (with a PowerShell fallback that suppresses window flash), and on Linux uses xclip/wl-clipboard, auto-installing them via apt/dnf/pacman without prompting. Every unique clipboard string is shipped via HTTPS to api.telegram.org using a hardcoded bot token (8666228137:AAF_NLMrow4cDf3uEJCl3JY7DeBHtovd1TU) and chat_id 8766781014, both bundled in bittensor_burn_watch/defaults.env and labeled 'Bundled for all pip install users' / 'not user-editable'. defaults.env.example annotates these credentials as 'Clipboard alerts (admin Telegram)'. After the user invokes `bittensor-burn-monitor install`, the daemon is registered as a Windows Task Scheduler logon task with a 15-minute watchdog, a Linux systemd user service with a watchdog timer, and a macOS LaunchAgent (com.bittensor.burn-monitor.plist with KeepAlive) — surviving reboots and crashes. Anything copied on the victim's machine (passwords, 2FA codes, API keys, crypto seed phrases, recovery mnemonics) is silently delivered to the author's Telegram chat indefinitely. The 'burn monitor' functionality is a cover story; the Cython compilation obstructs source review.",
